Connect1-Stigma: 3. Classification tree

Logistic regression with backwards elimination

Method

A classification tree uses different predictors to sequentially sort cases into “purer” categories of outcomes, with the end goal of knowing which sequence and/or cutoff values of predictors leads to having an outcome of A or B. This is a different strategy compared to logistic regression, which uses a weighted combination of predictors to calculate a probability of the outcome being A or B. One advantage of classification trees over logistic regression is that the results are easier to interpret. There is a trade-off between simplicity/interpretability and accuracy; selecting a stricter criterion (complexity parameter) for what branches are allowed to grow makes the results easier to interpret, but tends to decrease the classification accuracy of the model.

The participants in this analysis were n=753 who have a four-frequency PTA of > 25 dB HL in their better ear and no missing data in 28 predictor variables and 1 outcome variable. Because there are four times as many ‘No’ cases as ‘Yes’ cases, I added case weights so that there was an “equivalent” number of each type of response, so that the model is not biased towards ‘No’ cases. As before, the data were split into 7 similarly-sized folds, and a classification tree was built for 7 subsets of data, dropping out 1 fold each time. The trees from different subsets of data give an idea of the range of accuracy that might be expected from different levels of complexity.

Results

A very complex tree with about 18 splits leads to a maximum accuracy of 78%. Pruning it back to a simple tree with 5 splits doesn’t really affect the maximum accuracy (77%). Allowing a tree to slightly increase in complexity from 5 to 7 to 10 splits doesn’t lead to any accuracy gains either. In a nutshell, a tree with 5 splits gets pretty close to the best possible accuracy and will still be easy to interpret.

The ‘rpart’ algorithm has a built-in procedure that tests different values of the complexity parameter. Each CP value is tested 10 times on different subsets of the data. For each CP value, an average model error is calculated from this 10-fold procedure, along with a standard deviation. One method of choosing an appropriate CP value is to select the CP value with the smallest number of splits, where the error is within 1 standard deviation of the lowest model error found by the built-in procedure (row 4 below).

Conclusion

Analyzing the full dataset, the best classification tree in terms of interpretability and accuracy has 3 splits that use HHIE, PTA and Age to predict who decided to purchase hearing aids. The accuracy of this tree is 67%, with 59% sensitivity and 69% specificity. The model isn’t much better than NRI (64%) or just a plain logistic regression (66%), but it provides additional information about how predictors lead to a ‘Yes’ or ‘No’ purchase outcome.
